# Runbook: External tracker quirks (GitHub, GitLab, Shortcut, Jira, ...)

## Gated transitions need worker-produced fields

Some trackers gate a status transition on custom fields — e.g. "QA/Deployment
notes must be filled before Code Review." If those fields are empty, the
`pr_opened` sync fails and escalates instead of silently skipping the
transition. The **worker** is responsible for producing those notes
(`--qa-notes`, `--deployment-notes` on `issue update`) before the transition
is expected to succeed.

Some trackers also require rich-text fields to be encoded as their
structured document format (e.g. Atlassian's ADF), not a plain string, even
when the field's reported schema type says `string`. A plain string can be
silently rejected or mangled — check the tracker's actual accepted payload
shape, not just its documented type.

## `tracker_sync` is reconciliation, not a push

`mcp__arbiter__tracker_sync` (CLI: `arb issue sync`) claims
assigned-but-untracked issues and closes orphaned ones. It does **not** push
field updates or force a status transition on the tracker side — don't
reach for it expecting a field-push or re-transition; use the
tracker-specific update path for that.

## Dependency link direction can be reversed from what you'd expect

When creating a cross-issue dependency link via a tracker's REST API (e.g.
"X blocks Y" / "X is blocked by Y"), the inward/outward parameter naming is
sometimes counterintuitive relative to the tracker's own documentation.
After creating a link, verify the human-readable direction in the tracker UI
rather than trusting the parameter names matched your intent.

## Numeric vs. string project/repo identifiers

Some trackers accept a `"group/project"`-style string in their web UI but
reject it (404) via the API, requiring the numeric project ID instead — and
won't auto-encode the string form for you. If a tracker API call 404s on an
otherwise-correct-looking reference, check whether it wants a numeric ID.

## Keep internal framing out of external comms

When a worker posts a comment to a coworker's GitHub PR, Slack thread, or
similar, don't let internal framing leak into the message ("per the team
lead," "my coordinator says..."). It reads oddly to the external party and
tends to get parroted back verbatim. Phrase it in the operator's own
first-person voice, as one collaborator to another.
